      "content": [
        {
          "anchor": "overview",
          "level": 2,
          "text": "Overview",
          "type": "heading"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "text": "Filter width and height can be either 3, 5, 7 or 9. If there are multiple channels in the source image, each channel is processed independently.",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "text": "A ",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "inlineContent": [
                {
                  "text": "separable",
                  "type": "text"
                }
              ],
              "type": "emphasis"
            },
            {
              "text": " convolution filter may perform better when done in two passes. . A convolution filter is separable if the ratio of filter values between all rows is constant over the whole row. For example, this edge detection filter:",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "identifier": "media-2556905",
              "metadata": {
                "anchor": "2556905",
                "title": "Figure 1"
              },
              "type": "image"
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "text": "Can instead be separated into the product of two vectors, like so:",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "identifier": "media-2556912",
              "metadata": {
                "anchor": "2556912",
                "title": "Figure 2"
              },
              "type": "image"
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "text": "And consequently can be done as two, one-dimensional convolution passes back to back on the same image. In this way, the number of multiplies (ignoring the fact that we could skip zeros here) is reduced from ",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "code": "3*3=9",
              "type": "codeVoice"
            },
            {
              "text": " to ",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "code": "3+3=6",
              "type": "codeVoice"
            },
            {
              "text": ". There are similar savings for addition. For large filters, the savings can be profound.",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        }
      ],
      "kind": "content"
    }
  ],
